      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <div class="content1">
        <h1>Commandant's Awards</h1>
       </div>
       <div class="accordion">
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Lemuel MacKennie Long Jarman Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established by Dr. F. G. Jarman in memory of his son, a member of the Class of 1943, who died as a result of an accident during equestrian instruction on March 31, 1940.&nbsp; Given to a member of the fourth class who has exhibited outstanding scholarship, conduct and character, the recipient receives a $100 credit towards tuition or fees.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The William Brent Bell ’67 </a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 1970 as a memorial to First Lieutenant Bell who was killed when his helicopter was shot down by enemy fire in Vietnam in March 1969.&nbsp; It was established by his parents, relatives, classmates and friends to recognize a Third Class Cadet who has shown excellence in military studies as did Lieutenant Bell while at VMI.&nbsp; The recipient receives a cash prize of $100 and an engraved saber.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The VMI Distinguished Third Class Leadership Award </a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established&nbsp; by Nathaniel W. Pendleton, Junior, VMI Class of 1957, to encourage and recognize praiseworthy leadership in the proper practical education, training and development of fourth class cadets by a member of the Third Class. It is given to a third class cadet who has participated as a member of the new cadet training cadre who has exhibited the most praiseworthy leadership. The award recipient will receive a cash prize of $250 and a collection of books on leadership.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Association of Military Colleges and Schools of the United States</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award is given to a graduating cadet who has demonstrated significant improvement in leadership skills. The award is a medal supplied by AMSCUS.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Purple Heart Scholarship</a>
         <div class="more">
          The Purple Heart Scholarship from The Association Of Military Colleges and Schools of the United States in recognition of outstanding leadership, exceptional service and distinctive performance in all areas of cadet life, and for valuable and unselfish support of Virginia Military Institute. The award is a check and a certificate.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Col. Thomas H. Trumps, ’79 Commandant of Cadets Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2014 by the Class of 1979. It is given to a graduating first class private who has accepted an active duty commission in one of the Armed Forces&nbsp; and has demonstrated active participation in and served in a leadership role in one of the VMI club sports. The recipient receives a check and a certificate.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Veteran's Recognition Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2012 by the Commandant of Cadets, Colonel Thomas H. Trumps, VMI Class of 1979, to recognize a cadet who is a veteran of active duty military service and has continued to serve through exemplary leadership and mentorship in the corps of cadets.&nbsp; The recipient will receive an engraved mug and a check.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Community Service</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2012 by the Commandant of Cadets, Colonel Thomas H. Trumps, VMI Class of 1979, to recognize a cadet who served as an emergency medical technician, firefighter or rescue squad member.&nbsp; The recipient will receive a personally embroidered medical travel kit and $100.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Fit Cadet Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2012 by the Commandant of Cadets, Colonel Thomas H. Trumps, VMI Class of 1979, to recognize the male and female cadets achieving the highest VFT score during the academic year.&nbsp; The recipients will receive an engraved sports bottle and a check.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The 3rd Class Marksmanship Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2012 by Colonel Thomas H. Trumps, ’79 to recognize the company with the highest scoring average with the M-16/AR-15 service rifle. The award is given to the company with the highest average score on the 25 meter alternate course “c” qualification target. Company scores also count towards the overall Commandant’s Cup award.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The North Post Challenge Award</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was established in 2012 by Colonel Thomas H. Trumps, ’79 to recognize the company team with the highest combined fitness and marksmanship score. The award is given to the company team with the highest score in the following events: swimming, foot march, trap shoot, rifle marksmanship, rock climbing, obstacle course, and confidence climb. Company score will also count towards the overall commandant’s cup award. The first, second and third place company teams will also receive individual hand crafted sheath knives.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">The Company Cup for Academic Achievement</a>
         <div class="more">
          This award was proposed in October 1969 by cadets Carson L. Tucker, First Battalion Commander and William P. Williams, First Battalion Adjutant who wrote, “for it is possible to utilize the company system here at VMI to influence the academic endeavors of at least fourth classmen, who are particularly impressionable during their first year at the Institute.&nbsp; By bringing academic achievement onto a par with military and physical training achievement, the importance of academic excellence (or, at least, academic stability) will be manifested to impressionable young cadets.”&nbsp; The Dean of the Faculty, Colonel James M. Morgan, agreed and the Company Cup was awarded for the first time on May 12, 1970, to Company D, commanded by Cadet Captain Robert F. E. Quinlan.&nbsp; The company with the highest combined average GPA for the fall and spring semesters is awarded the company cup upon which their company and year is engraved and a distinctive red streamer is displayed on their guide-on upon award and during the following academic year.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Commandant's Cup</a>
         <div class="more">
          <p>On January 30th, 1959, The Commandant Of Cadets, Colonel Glover S. Johns Junior, wrote a letter to General William H. Milton Junior, VMI’s Eighth Superintendent, proposing the establishment the Commandant’s Cup awarded “to the cadet company making the best score in certain aspects of physical training.”&nbsp; His proposal was approved.&nbsp; Colonel Johns designed the sterling silver trophy, approximately 18 inches in height, bearing the distinctive VMI monogram, to be given to the company excelling each year in physical fitness.&nbsp; His objective was improving the physical condition of the corps as a whole.&nbsp;</p>
          <p>The cup is engraved as follows:&nbsp; Virginia Military Institute Commandant’s Cup presented annually to the company most outstanding in physical training and fair specimens of citizen-soldiers.&nbsp; The awarding of this cup was discontinued in 1970 except for 1979 and 1985. </p>
          <p>The company with the highest average score on the VFT for the academic year was awarded the cup.&nbsp; In 2012 the Third Class Marksmanship competition and North Post Challenge&nbsp; results were added to the computation along with the company VFT pass rate.&nbsp;</p>
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Garnett Andrews Cup</a>
         <div class="more">
          Mr. Garnett Andrews, VMI Class of 1890, donated the Garnett Andrews Cup in 1915 which was presented to the company scoring highest in military efficiency throughout the year.&nbsp; Scoring for the Garnett Andrews Cup competition is based on the company’s general efficiency as a military unit which includes the company’s performance in drill, ceremonies, parade appearance, meal march-downs and guard mounts.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div>
         <a href="#" class="readMore">Superientendent's Cup</a>
         <div class="more">
          This cup is awarded to the company with the highest cumulative point total in the three scored areas of academics, military efficiency and physical fitness.&nbsp; The superintendent’s cup is also an incentive for companies to “keep trying” during the year since the award is based on the highest 
          <strong>cumulative</strong> point total across the three areas not the highest point total of the individual cups.
         </div>
        </div>
       </div> 
      </div> 
     </div> 
    </div> 
